{
  "texts": [
    "Two studies revealed that some airplane pilots who spent most of their flying careers operating highly automated airplanes performed poorly in their unaided manual flying skills (Casner et al., 2014; Ebbatson et al., 2010).",
    "This example highlights that we normatively prefer that airline pilots know how to fly manually in case of a bug in the autopilot system, and thus we negatively evaluate their brain-based cognitive deskilling.",
    "For at least three reasons, the same goes for other brain-based cognitive abilities that may be still important to develop independently of their potential for at least three reasons.",
    "First, there might be cases of technological failure or hacking.",
    "Second, cognitive extensions may not be neutral with respect to the development of the overall cognitive character, potentially giving rise to different kinds of cognitive trade-offs."
  ]
}